posts.body:
>>0c743928-dde1-482e-8bc5-95c5651aac64
I've given up on government. Anywhere you look around the world - government behavior is identical. They always seek MOAR.

So it's a waste of time trying to change such behavior. Seems to be innate to humans.

The single accidental stroke of genius humankind ever had was our Bill of Rights. Why we need to start expanding it. Use it to take dangerous powers our of the hands of government. No blasting caps for kiddies.

Immediate candidates:

1. No penalties for ingestion of any kind.
2. No home invasions.
3. No forced association.
4. No government racial preference.

I'd add sanctity of communications - but it's too easy for them to cheat and hide it. You should only make rules you can enforce.

Adding to the Bill of Rights would keep them busy and out of our hair for 20 years. They'd be swamped repealing all the dumbass laws they passed.

It would take some time to deprogram our population. Those repeated lies often become dogmas. "Civil rights" will be especially difficult for many to unlearn and erase.

I'd like a future where a store owner could choose to accept a diverse customer base - or not. One where he could exclude a prospective customer for ANY reason. Ditto hires...an employer picks for his goals - not some political faction's goals. He'd still be subject to union organizing and that's enough. No need for government pile on.

I'm sure those jackals of the credit industry would be happy to supply lists of unpleasant customers. While I recognize in a way that this is similar to China's social credit system - there would be no government control. And idiots who misused that data would just hurt themselves.

Don't like them spying on you? Start paying by cash, and not racking up lawsuits.

Better be nice to everyone, because once you get the reputation as a cheat or a thief - your lifetime options will change drastically. 

Not much different from a world where everyone is armed - and well behaved.

It was a mistake to control human behavior via centralized government. Much better executed by local individuals just trying to live their lives without trouble.

The government has accomplished nothing other than keeping their jobs. Worse, the competence level of government workers is in steep decline - making a bad system intolerable.

posts.subject: Job Creators Network video wanted to show how small businesses are hurt by riots. YouTube restricted it.
posts.body:
https://archive.vn/uAgtz

JCN’s video that is now being labelled inappropriate by YouTube is titled “Keep America America: Is Your City Next?” and is 30 seconds long. It shows several instances of violence in the riots that have been taking place across the country.

While labelling a video “inappropriate” would not essentially kill it on the platform, it would just make it harder to promote or propagate to a wider set of audience. When videos are restricted from being promoted by YouTube, it becomes difficult to boost their reach and so an “inappropriate content” label does a great extent of damage to creators on the platform.

With the JCN wanting to spread awareness about the rioting and discourage people from destroying property, a restriction such as this makes that more difficult.

“An inappropriate content warning does not stop the video from being viewed, but users must log in and click that they ‘understand and wish to proceed’ before viewing. This warning prevents videos from being promoted, reducing their reach and view count. JCN notes how this censorship neither applies to left-wing videos that depict protest violence nor the original news videos from which the rioting clips are taken. JCN calls on YouTube to treat all political content fairly and without partisan bias,” said JCN.

Furthermore, the JCN also said that platforms such as YouTube should remain politically neutral and allow people from all political spectrums to express their viewpoints without the fear of censorship.

“They should uphold the values of free speech that are the basis of their revenue model and popularity. Social media’s widespread censorship of conservative views demonstrates society’s slide away from the values of free speech. President Trump should nominate a strong defender of the First Amendment to the Supreme Court to help reestablish this fundamental right of all Americans.”
